  "prompt": "Are ductile metals also malleable?",
  "response": "Yes, ductile metals are typically also malleable. Ductility refers to a material's ability to deform under tensile stress, enabling it to be stretched into wires without breaking. Malleability, on the other hand, is the ability to deform under compressive stress, which allows a metal to be hammered or rolled into thin sheets. \n\nMost ductile metals, such as gold, silver, aluminum, and copper, exhibit both properties, making them useful for various applications, including electrical wiring and metalworking. However, the degree of ductility and malleability can vary between different metals and alloys.",
